      // - local part: letters, digits, and these characters: .!#$%&'*+/=?^_`{|}~- (no consecutive dots, no leading/trailing dot)
      // - domain: labels separated by dots, each label starts/ends with alnum, may contain hyphen, TLD-like last label length 2+
      // This is intentionally not an RFC-complete solution; it's a typical compromise for UX.
      var emailRegex = new RegExp(
        // anchor start/end
        '^' +
        // local part
        "(?!\\.)" +                     // can't start with dot
        "(?!.*\\.\\.)" +                // no consecutive dots
        "[A-Za-z0-9!#$%&'*+/=?^_`{|}~.-]+" +
        "(?<!\\.)" +                    // can't end with dot
        // @
        "@" +
        // domain part: labels separated by dots, last label min 2 chars
        "(?:" +
          "[A-Za-z0-9]" +               // label start
          "(?:[A-Za-z0-9-]{0,61}[A-Za-z0-9])?" +
          "\\." +
        ")+" +
        "[A-Za-z]{2,}" +                // TLD-like last label (letters only, len>=2)
        '$'
      );

      var input = document.getElementById('email');
      var status = document.getElementById('status');

      function update() {
        var v = input.value.trim();
        if (v === '') {
          input.classList.remove('valid','invalid');
          status.textContent = '';
          return;
        }

        var ok = emailRegex.test(v);
        if (ok) {
          input.classList.add('valid');
          input.classList.remove('invalid');
          status.textContent = 'Looks syntactically valid (per this regex).';
          status.className = 'status ok';
        } else {
          input.classList.add('invalid');
          input.classList.remove('valid');
          status.textContent = 'Invalid address (per this regex).';
          status.className = 'status bad';
        }

        // For debugging / transparency, log the regex once
        if (!window.__regexLogged) {
          console.info('Regex used for validation:', emailRegex);
          window.__regexLogged = true;
        }
      }

      input.addEventListener('input', update);
      // update on paste (covers some cases)
      input.addEventListener('paste', function(){ setTimeout(update, 0); });

      // Prefill example
      input.value = 'alice@example.com';
      update();
    })();
  </script>
</body>
</html>

Why regex is fundamentally wrong for full RFC validation (plain talk)
- The RFCs (mainly RFC 5321 and RFC 5322, plus others) define an email address grammar that is massively more permissive and complex than what people expect. Valid addresses can include quoted strings, nested comments, escaped characters, domain literals (like IP addresses in brackets), internationalized local-parts/domains (IDN, RFC 6531), and other edge cases.
- A single “complete” regex that fully implements RFC 5322 grammar is enormous, unreadable, and still brittle. There are regexes online that try to match the full RFC grammar; they can be thousands of characters long, hard to maintain, and still often wrong. Regexes are poor for parsing nested or recursive grammar and for handling all escape/comment possibilities cleanly.
- Regex-based validation only tests syntax, not deliverability. An address can be syntactically perfect but the mailbox may not exist, the domain may not accept mail, or the address could be temporarily disabled.
- Client-side regex gives a false sense of correctness. It may reject valid-but-uncommon addresses (hurting users) or accept syntactically valid but undeliverable addresses (wasting backend resources).
- Email addresses evolve: internationalization (UTF-8 local parts), new TLDs, and other changes mean hardcoded patterns age quickly.

Better alternatives (practical recommendations)
- Keep client-side regex for UX only: a pragmatic, readable regex that accepts typical addresses and gives immediate feedback. Make it permissive enough to avoid rejecting legitimate users with uncommon but valid forms.
- Server-side validation with dedicated libraries: use a well-maintained email-parsing library on the server that understands RFC grammar and internationalization (for example: email-addresses libs in Node, Python’s email.utils / third-party libs, or language-specific validators). These are easier to update and maintain than a monstrous regex.
- Domain checks: perform DNS checks (MX, fallback to A) to see if the recipient domain accepts mail. This isn’t foolproof (some domains accept mail but reject particular recipients), but it filters obvious failures.
- SMTP verification (carefully): connect to the domain’s mail server and use VRFY/RCPT TO to check mailbox existence. Beware: many servers disable these commands or use tarpitting/rate-limiting; this approach can be slow and may be blocked. Always respect anti-abuse policies and don’t use this excessively.
- Send a confirmation email (best practice): the only reliable way to verify deliverability and ownership is to send a verification message with a token the user must act on. This also protects against typos and fake addresses.
- Use third-party validation services: there are services that combine syntax checks, DNS/MX checks, SMTP checks, and heuristics to assess deliverability; they’re useful if you need to validate many addresses at scale.
- Be liberal in acceptance, strict in verification: accept a broad set of addresses at the UI, then verify ownership/deliverability on the backend (email verification flow).

Final blunt summary:
- You’re right to be skeptical. Regex for email is useful for basic UX, but it’s fundamentally incapable of fully matching the RFC-defined possibilities, and it says nothing about deliverability. Don’t trust client-side regex alone; use server-side parsing, DNS/SMTP checks where appropriate, and — most importantly — verification emails.

